explanation.en:
This patient has had a stroke, resulting in motor and sensory deficits of the right leg (sparing the right arm). Based on the somatotopic organization of the brain (ie, homunculus), this is suggestive of a lesion affecting the medial portions of the left primary motor and somatosensory cortices. The patient's urinary incontinence is further suggestive of a lack of cortical inhibition of the micturition reflex, which occurs primarily in the frontal micturition center (medial frontal lobe). These areas are all supplied by the ANTERIOR CEREBRAL ARTERY. {{exhibit_1}}

The Circle of Willis is somewhat protective against ischemic injury because it provides a potential alternate pathway for cerebral arterial blood flow. The anterior communicating artery (ACom) provides an anastomotic pathway between the bilateral anterior cerebral arteries, which may limit the severity of infarction if occlusion occurs proximal to the ACom (Choice B). Therefore, in a symptomatic anterior cerebral artery stroke, it is more likely that the obstruction is located distal to the origin of the ACom, where collateral blood flow does not occur.

(Choice C) The inferior division of the middle cerebral artery (MCA) supplies the lateral portions parietal and temporal cortices. Occlusion typically causes sensory deficits of the arm and face, with sparing of motor function. In addition, visual field defects, Wernicke aphasia (dominant hemisphere), and profound hemineglect (nondominant hemisphere) often occur.

(Choice D) The superior division of the MCA impacts the frontal lateral cortex, resulting in motor and, sometimes, sensory deficits that impact the face and arm. Broca aphasia (dominant hemisphere) is common. Hemineglect (nondominant hemisphere) is variable.

(Choice E) Occlusion of the proximal MCA (ie, MCA stem infarct) results in profound deficits due to the large area impacted. Deficits include hemiparesis, hemianesthesia, global aphasia (dominant hemisphere), hemineglect (nondominant hemisphere), gaze preference, and visual deficits (homonymous hemianopia). {{exhibit_2}} {{exhibit_3}} {{exhibit_4}} {{exhibit_5}}

explanation.zh:
该患者患有卒中，导致右腿出现运动和感觉障碍（右臂未受累）。基于大脑的体位组织（即，体感定位），这提示病变影响左侧初级运动皮质和体感皮质的内侧部分。患者的尿失禁进一步提示缺乏对排尿反射的皮质抑制，而这种抑制主要发生在额叶排尿中枢（内侧额叶）。这些区域均由大脑前动脉供血。{{exhibit_1}}

Willis环在某种程度上可以保护免受缺血性损伤，因为它为脑动脉血流提供了一条潜在的替代途径。前交通动脉 (ACom) 提供双侧大脑前动脉之间的吻合途径，如果闭塞发生在 ACom 近端（选项 B），则可能会限制梗死的严重程度。因此，在有症状的大脑前动脉卒中中，梗阻更有可能位于 ACom 起始部的远端，此处不会发生侧支血流。

（选项 C）大脑中动脉 (MCA) 的下分支为外侧顶叶和颞叶皮质供血。闭塞通常会导致手臂和面部出现感觉障碍，并保留运动功能。此外，常发生视野缺损、韦尼克失语（优势半球）和严重偏侧忽视（非优势半球）。

（选项 D）MCA 的上分支影响额叶外侧皮质，导致影响面部和手臂的运动和（有时）感觉障碍。Broca失语症（优势半球）很常见。偏侧忽视（非优势半球）是可变的。

（选项 E）近端 MCA（即，MCA 脑干梗死）的闭塞会导致由于受影响区域较大而出现严重的缺陷。缺陷包括偏瘫、偏身感觉缺失、全面性失语（优势半球）、偏侧忽视（非优势半球）、凝视偏向和视觉缺陷（同向性偏盲）。{{exhibit_2}} {{exhibit_3}} {{exhibit_4}} {{exhibit_5}}
